{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"966ea145-fb86-4759-8f59-b24bdf7c39b8","content":"`SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the page tells it **which edges to pad for**, but it doesn't make child views extend behind system bars on its own. You likely need a combination of things:\n\n**1. Hide Shell/Navigation chrome** (if using Shell):\n```xml\n<ContentPage ...\n             Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n             Shell.TabBarIsVisible=\"False\">\n```\n\n**2. Use `IgnoreSafeArea` on the layout holding your image:**\n```xml\n<Grid IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\">\n    <Image Source=\"{Binding Photo}\"\n           Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n</Grid>\n```\n\n**3. Make sure the page has no explicit `Padding`:**\n```xml\n<ContentPage Padding=\"0\" ...>\n```\n\n**4. On Android (pre-15), enable edge-to-edge in your `MainActivity`:**\n```csharp\nprotected override void OnCreate(Bundle? savedInstanceState)\n{\n    base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);\n    AndroidX.Core.View.WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(Window, false);\n}\n```\n\nOn Android 15+ (API 35), edge-to-edge is enforced automatically, so step 4 is only needed for older targets.\n\n**TL;DR** — `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` stops the *page* from adding safe-area padding, but `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on the inner layout is what actually lets content draw behind the status/nav bars. You typically need both, plus hiding any Shell chrome.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8233fe17-ae81-419c-a992-87471866e15c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making content go edge-to-edge in a .NET MAUI app on .NET 10, going behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but still see padding.\n\nThis is about .NET MAUI's edge-to-edge/full-screen display APIs. In .NET 10 (which is the upcoming version), there have been changes to how edge-to-edge content works, particularly on Android where Android 15+ enforces edge-to-edge by default.\n\nLet me think about what I know:\n\nIn .NET MAUI (.NET 9+), there's been work on edge-to-edge support. \n\nThe main properties controlling this behavior are `SafeAreaEdges` which determines which edges respect safe area insets, and `IgnoreSafeArea` on individual views for more granular control. On Android specifically, apps targeting API 35+ get edge-to-edge rendering by default starting with Android 15, and .NET MAUI has been updating its APIs to handle this—including new `HybridSafeArea` functionality and adjustments to how edge-to-edge works in .NET 10.\n\nBut the user's issue is that even with `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage, there's still padding around the content. This could be coming from several places: the Shell or NavigationPage might be adding their own chrome, the Android window might not be configured to draw behind system bars, or parent layouts could be introducing additional padding. I need to think through what's actually happening in .NET 10 MAUI specifically. - Android 15+ enforces edge-to-edge, so the app draws behind system bars by default\n- But MAUI by default adds padding to account for system bars (safe area)\n- You need to opt out of this padding\n\nThe solution typically involves setting `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the page, but I also need to consider that the parent layout might still be applying safe area padding, and platform-specific configuration could be required—especially on Android where I may need to explicitly configure the window for edge-to-edge rendering if not on Android 15+. I'm realizing the distinction between the page itself ignoring safe areas versus the content within it—the user might need to remove padding from the ContentPage and set `IgnoreSafeArea` on the Image or its container, or handle platform-specific window configuration to truly achieve edge-to-edge rendering in .NET 10 MAUI.\n\nThe most likely culprits are a NavigationPage or Shell adding its own chrome at the top, explicit padding on the page itself, or the need to set `IgnoreSafeArea` on the layout/view rather than just `SafeAreaEdges` on the page.\n\nFor .NET 10, I'd recommend disabling the navigation and tab bars in Shell, setting `IgnoreSafeArea` on the Grid, and then handling platform-specific window configuration—particularly on Android where the system UI visibility flags need to be adjusted to allow content to extend into the system areas.","outputTokens":2220,"requestId":"F3C1:1A8A2F:1F81DE3:23669B8:69E81CB6"},"id":"b541ef0a-94a2-4d99-8da2-bdf3d2650ceb","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:57:03.146Z","parentId":"be4394c8-d6a2-4833-ab36-9ef30208073d"}
